If you open multiple connections and close at least one connection opened before the last one.
You will no longer have access to the last one as you will get the ValueError out of the 
def _resolve_index(self, index) method which is verifying the index against the len of the connections list:
     
    if not 0 < index <= len(self._connections):
        raise ValueError

It seems to be an bug at SSHConnectionCache implementation.

The new index is now for sure generated correctly with searching at the connection config
with:

    return next((x for x in self._connections if x.config._config['index'].value == index), None)

But self._resolve_alias_or_index(alias_or_index) is called before and will not allow any index higher than the _connections list len.

    def get_connection(self, alias_or_index=None):
        if alias_or_index is None:
            if not self:
                self.current.raise_error()
            return self.current
        try:
            index = self._resolve_alias_or_index(alias_or_index)
        except ValueError:
            raise RuntimeError("Non-existing index or alias '%s'." % alias_or_index)
        return next((x for x in self._connections if x.config._config['index'].value == index), None)

This means : as the self._resolve_alias_or_index(alias_or_index) is called first and it raises a Value error you will have no access to indexes which are originally higher than the current index for that connection even this could be generated correctly searching then connections list by compare with the connection config index value.

Currently, to run command as root the following code is needed:
```
    Open Connection    ${HOST}
    Login    ${USER}    ${PASSWORD}
    Write    su root
    Write    ${ROOT_PASS}
    Write    whoami
    ${output}=    Read
    Log    ${output}
    Close Connection
```

How about adding "Execute Command As Root" keyword to SSHLibrary?
